"'''''Racaille'''''" is a [[French language|French]] [[Pejorative|derogatory term]] that roughly means ''rabble'' (although some translate it as ''riff-raff'' or ''dregs'') and has been specifically associated in [[France]] since the [[nineties]] with residents of the poor ''[[banlieue]]s'' or ''cités''. It gained international notoriety when used by French interior minister, [[Nicolas Sarkozy]], to describe the residents of crime-ridden neighborhoods.  His comment is widely attributed to causing the [[2005 Paris riots]] in France.

''Racaille'' and its ''[[verlan]]'' form "'''''caillera'''''" are also widely used to name the culture, and particularly the clothing style, associated with the ''cités''.

